,Recommended,428900,29593668,Posted: 30 January,all,Titanic21,"Just some short review for ""Intralism""'s brother... Or shouldn't it be sister?Nevermind. Linea, the game (The comma is a part of the name, NEVER dare to leave it out) is pretty much 2.5D Super Hexagon. It's not as good but also a lot of fun.While the first two levels are pretty easy, this game is pretty, pretty hard overall. As mentioned, use Super Hexagon, insert it into a 3D-printer, nail what you get onto a skateboard, push it right into the direction of a camcorder, motion capture the result and do some programming using the ""Unity-Engine"". This game's pretty much what you should get.Graphics are nothing special, but if you wanted a game with astonishing graphics you surely wouldn't be here, so this point is kind of forgettable.The soundtrack is not really my style, but it would be unfair to dislike it therefore. What I mean is that the melodies are quite catchy, but the chiptune-instrumentation pretty much ruin them for me, nevermind that.As already said, the difficulty is pretty... High. If you can't get enough of the main levels, buy the DLC. THEN we can talk again. I mean, there are harder games, of course, but in a scale of one  to ten i'd give Linea's difficulty level a 7,5. (Main game: 7; DLC: 8; external review coming in the future) Prepare yourself for some hours of training.Funny indeed are the achievements. You can literally gain half of them without really succeeding. That's not a joke, It happend to me exactly that way. I mean, look it up by yourself, there's an achievement for starting the game.Enough said.For 2$ you can't get wrong.If you like challenges you should accept this one. I wish you great luck. Over and out."
